   "hider_text": "The ceiling hums with the breath of old plaster, soft and slow, like something stirring underneath the floorboards. There’s a crack in the wall near the window, just wide enough to catch the light when the sun leans in at three. That crack is warm — not hot, but alive with the memory of heat from a long-ago fire.  \n\nIn the corner, a chair sits turned / The metal frame hums in the silence after rain, not from motion, but from the way it holds the air—tight, like breath held too long. It leans against the wall where the paint flaked once, now powdered into dust that settles like ash. The joints press gently against the corner of the room, fingers of rusted steel touching the wood of the shelf.  \n\nYou can feel / The wind hums through the canyon walls, low and dry as a breath held too long. It doesn’t blow — it *sings* in the hollows between stones, a sound like pebbles grinding underfoot in a place where no feet have tread.  \n\nThe sun climbs the ridge, not with fire, but with a slow, golden patience. It paints the sand in layers —",
   "seeker_text": "The weight of a single breath held too long.  \n\nNot the air. Not the lungs. But the silence *after* you exhale — the tiny pause where the world seems to absorb the sound, like a sponge. That moment when your body remembers it’s alive, and the room holds its breath with you.  \n\nIt’s not warmth. It’s not cold. It’s just there — / The shape of a door hinge when touched with a fingertip — not the metal, but the way it *bends* slightly under pressure, like a folded paper leaf. The warmth of the wood beneath it, the quiet hum of the house settling at 3 a.m., the way the hinge doesn’t just hold a door, but *witnesses* the turning of it — the slow / The silence after the last breath of the old clock in the attic.  \nNot the silence of emptiness, but the one that feels like a held-in sigh—thick, warm, and just slightly damp. It’s not empty. It’s *full* of what was never said, of the way the dust motes moved in the beam of light just before the power cut out."
  },
